<h3 class=3D"SubHeading"><a id=3D"WhatIs">What is a Sector of a Circle?</a>=
</h3>
<div class=3D"PageInfo">
<p>A sector is a section (or part) of a circle.</p>
<p>Sectors have central angles and radius values which we can use to find t=
he area.</p>
<p class=3D"center-align">
<img alt=3D"sector of a circle labelled image" class=3D"ImageBdCt ss-lazy" =
data-src=3D"https://www.math-salamanders.com/image-files/sector-of-a-circle=
-labelled.gif" height=3D"193" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAA=
ACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=3D=3D" title=3D"sector of a circle label=
led image" width=3D"196">
</p>
<p>In the image above you can see the light brown sector of the circle (cal=
led a minor sector) with a central angle of =CE=B8=C2=B0</p>
<p>There is also a larger white sector (called a major sector) which has a =
central angle of (360 - =CE=B8)=C2=B0</p>
<p>Sectors can have any central angle of up to 360=C2=B0</p>
<p>The central angle can also be measured in radians - when it is measured =
in radians, the angle can be any value up to 2=CF=80 radians.</p>
<p>When the central angle is measured in radians, the formula for the area =
is slightly different.</p>
</div><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_4_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad adthrive-s=
ticky-container adthrive-content adthrive-content-4 adthrive-ad-cls"></div>
